<section id="about-us-faq" class="mb-5">
  <div class="container fs-5">
    <h1>FAQ's about Snehaanchal</h1>
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ1" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #1 What is the nature of the service/care provided by a hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ1">
      <div class="card card-body">
        The first goal is to relieve the patient of pain and any distressing symptoms. Once this is achieved, we help
        them
        and their family members to come to terms with the disease and its prognosis. The aim is to gradually make them
        accept the final eventuality so that they are at peace with themselves, their families, and their God.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ2" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #2 What services are not provided by the hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ2">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Treatment methods of cancer, like surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, etc., are not provided at the
        hospice.
        Further, complementary medicine, proton therapy, clinical trials, and cutting-edge technologies are also not
        provided
        in a hospice.No life-extending measures, like a ventilator, blood transfusion, and oxygen are provided. The
        philosophy of end-life-care envisages that no life-limiting or life-extending measures will be deployed.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ3" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #3 What are opiates and what is morphine? Is there a possibility of getting addicted to morphine?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ3">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Opiates, like Morphine, are the best drugs for controlling severe pain. Opiates help the patient to get relief
        from
        severe pain when all the other painkillers prove ineffective. Opiates like Morphine do not cause addiction when
        used
        to relieve cancer pain. In fact, if the pain is substantially reduced and the patient feels fine, it may not be
        necessary to continue with morphine as other painkillers may suffice.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ4" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #4 What are the other misconceptions about opiates and morphine?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ4">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Other misconceptions:
        <ul>
          <li>
            That large doses of morphine are administered to patients:The patient is put on morphine only when other
            painkillers prove ineffective. Doses are set by doctors according to the level of pain experienced by the
            patient
            and as per WHO guidelines for pain management. It is administered after close observation and careful
            assessment
            of the patient’s pain. Not less, not more.
          </li>
          <li>
            That patients become drowsy:It is not true in every case. Most patients are very alert and active all the
            time
            after consuming opiates.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ5" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #5 What charges are payable for Snehaanchal Hospice service?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ5">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Snehaanchal does not charge any money from the patient. All services provided by it, including medicines, food,
        stay,
        care, etc., are completely free. Food (free of charge) is presently provided to patients, whereas for the
        caregivers,
        food is currently provided by voluntary groups of people. Stay is free of charge for family members.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ6" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #6 What are the criteria of admission to the hospice? When is the best time to get admitted to a hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ6">
      <div class="card card-body">
        The criteria are::
        <ul>
          <li>
            The patient must be a cancer sufferer facing severe distressing physical, psychosocial & emotional symptoms.
          </li>
          <li>
            Sometimes a patient can be admitted for short durations to provide respite to the family members or
            caregivers.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ7" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #7 Who provides medical nursing care in a hospice? Who provides psychosocial counseling and support?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ7">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Doctors who are especially trained and experienced in thepalliative treatment and care provide medical
        care.Sisters,
        Catholic nuns of SMMI order, who are also well-qualified/experienced in nursing, provide nursing care.A trained
        and
        experienced psychologist or social worker provides psychosocial counseling.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ8" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #8 What kind of nutrition is provided in a hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ8">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Hygienically prepared, nutritious& balanced diet is provided to the patients. Family members do not need to
        bring
        food for the patients. Patients can also req for a special food of their liking. However, only vegetarian food
        is
        provided.
      </div>
      <hr />
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ9" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #9 Are the relatives allowed to stay at the hospice & is food provided to them?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ9">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Yes, the relatives are allowed to stay with the patients. There is also a dormitory for the relatives of
        outstation
        patients. Food is also provided to the relatives by voluntary groups of people.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ10" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #10 Once admitted, can a person take discharge from the hospice & go home?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ10">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Yes, the patient is always free to go back to their home whenever they feel like it. If the family members are
        willing to take the patient home, the patient is allowed to go back home. <br />
        Before sending the patient home, the caregivers at hospice ensure that family members are fully trained to do
        wound-dressing, feeding, managing catheter, etc., so that they face no difficulty on this count while at home.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ11" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #11 Can a discharged patient seek re-admission to the hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ11">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Yes, hospice is more like a home for a patient and if the distressing symptoms re-appear, the patient is always
        welcomed back.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ12" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #12 What is done in the event of death of a person admitted to the hospice?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ12">
      <div class="card card-body">
        The relatives are quickly informed. Also the deceased is given a bath and laid in the room where prayer is
        undertaken
        for his or her soul and then handed over to the family.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ13" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #13 When is the right time to start Home Care?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ13">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Palliative care can run complementary to curative treatment. If the patient, while on curative treatment or
        otherwise, is suffering from symptoms like pain, vomiting, nausea, bleeding or has a fungating tumor needing
        regular
        dressing, then it is advisable to ask for a Home Palliative Care. It must also be sought when the patient is
        suffering from severe anxiety and depression arising because of the disease, affecting both him/her and his/her
        family.
      </div>
      <hr />
    </div>
    <hr />
    <a data-bs-toggle="collapse" href="#FAQ14" role="button" class="d-block text-decoration-none">
      #14 Does Snehaanchal Home team provide treatment/cure to the patient with cancer?
    </a>
    <div class="collapse" id="FAQ14">
      <div class="card card-body">
        Treatment for cancer is not provided at all. Treatment is provided to reduce the distressing symptoms, be it
        physical
        or psychological.
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
  </div>
  <hr />
</section>

